-- #607, two-hop FORWARDED shape (PR #617 craft review). A `=>`-signed function
-- delegating to another on the same type vars — the "#23 two-hop forward" shape
-- `forwardedObls`/`allCallObls` exists for.
--
-- This pins the DIAGNOSTIC COUNT, which is the whole point: an exit-code gate
-- cannot see this bug (3 diagnostics and 1 diagnostic are both REJECT). The
-- correct output is exactly ONE `No impl of Ix for String Bool`.
--
-- allCallObls used to flat-map a joint obligation vector into one synthetic 1-ary
-- entry PER ARGUMENT, hardcoding ["a"]/TyVar "a". Each shard landed on a bound
-- tyvar, so boundTyvarIds SUCCEEDED and `Ix a i` was registered as `Ix a` AND
-- `Ix i` alongside the real joint entry. dedupVecObls compares whole lists, so
-- [a], [i] and [a,i] are three distinct entries and none collapse; they then take
-- three different checkCallObligationsU keys ("Ix,String" / "Ix,Bool" /
-- "Ix,String,Bool"), so the vector-wide dedup cannot merge them either.
-- Result: ONE violation reported THREE times, breaking the invariant
-- checkCallObligationsU's own comment states — "the oracle raises ONE error per
-- missing impl" — and `helper` displayed as `(Ix a, Ix a b, Ix b) =>` at exit 0
-- in the SATISFIED case. The synthetic-entry detour is gone: a forwarded predicate
-- is now mapped to bound tyvar ids DIRECTLY off the pendingCallObligations delta
-- (forwardedVecObls), which already carries its joint `List Mono`, so the vector
-- survives whole at every arity. See the unsigned sibling
-- (multiparam_constraint_forwarded_unsigned) for the shape that has no declared
-- context to fall back on.
interface Ix a i where
  ix : a -> i -> Int

impl Ix Int Int where
  ix a i = a + i

twoParamOk : Ix a i => a -> i -> Int
twoParamOk a i = ix a i

helper : Ix a i => a -> i -> Int
helper x y = twoParamOk x y

main = println (helper "hi" True)
